We are also starting to share sneak peaks of ENSv2. @domicoeth & @erni_eth explained our rationale and design principles in creating two new apps: the ENS App and the ENS Explorer. They also invited people back to the booth for 1:1 demos and testing. üëÄ

Get excited for the first public alpha releases in early 2026.
A crypto event is not without some sort of natural or technical disaster. At this year‚Äôs Devconnect, there was a massive Cloudflare outage on Day 2.
@schmidsi live demoed how ENS, @Filecoin Onchain Cloud, and @safe can be used to create a simple and secure deployment pipeline to publish websites and apps in a decentralized way.
Perhaps the buzziest topic was payment and identity standards for AI agents on blockchain rails, like ERC-8004 and x402. Agents can act autonomously, but their identity, attribution, and payments need to be onchain. That is exactly where ENS fits.

@schmidsi moderated a packed ERC-8004 panel with MetaMaskAI, Nethermind, Flashbots, and the EF, digging into how agents anchor identity and trust.
The L2 space has grown enormously over the last few @EFDevcon events, and it's clearer than ever that we need ENS as a cross-chain identity standard, not tied to a single network.

@gregskril ran a hands-on workshop on L2 primary names for @Arbitrum, @Optimism, @Scroll_ZKP , @LineaBuild, and @Base.
ENS Labs met with @Nethermind after announcing that @Namechain, the upcoming ENS ZK rollup, will run on Nethermind Surge, built on @taikoxyz.
